TY  - JOUR
AU  - Lazear, Edward P.
T1  - Educational Production*
PY  - 2001
Y1  - 2001/08/01
DO  - 10.1162/00335530152466232
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 116
IS  - 3
SP  - 777
EP  - 803
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Classroom education has public good aspects. The technology is such that when one student disrupts the class, learning is reduced for all other students. A disruption model of educational production is presented. It is shown that optimal class size is larger for better-behaved students, which helps explain why it is difficult to find class size effects in the data. Additionally, the role of discipline is analyzed and applied to differences in performance of Catholic and public schools. An empirical framework is discussed where the importance of sorting students, teacher quality, and other factors can be assessed.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/00335530152466232
ER  - 



